Happened across this in a bookshop yesterday. I looked at the cover, and how could I resist? It was rather expensive, so I charged it to Thorn's credit card while she wasn't looking. 'Sweet Gwendoline' is a collection of work by John Alexander Scott Coutts, aka 'John Willie'. It's really rather sweet. Poor Gwendoline, and other girls who look a lot like her, get into all sorts of scrapes. Gwendoline is constantly being kidnapped and tied up by the evil Sir d'Arcy d'Arcy, Countess 'M', and their minions. Except when she's being rescued by the beautiful and mysterious Agent U89. (Whose number changes several times, continuity not being J.W.'s strong point.) And occasionally tied up again by U89. You get the idea. All very inspirational. Sadly, Willie was an appalling businessman. Most of these stories are incomplete because money ran out and magazines folded on him before he could finish them. But his inability to plan ahead does give them a certain naive charm - who can forget Faithful Fred, the square-jawed hero who appears proudly in the cast list but never actually makes it into the story? (I suspect Willie found he preferred Agent U89, and who can blame him?) Plenty of damsels. Bucketloads of distress. Cute '20s fashions. Who could ask for more? Oh, Thorn...

Good evening to you, ladies and gentlemen. Thorn and I have decided to experiment with keeping these journals. We are the Recreation Officers of the Colossus, the world's finest (and only) giant-turtle-based luxury vessel. As such we are tasked with organising diversion and entertainment for the passengers... and, more importantly, for ourselves. Would you like to help us? We are also highly respected fetish models, resident in the fine city of Melbourne, although temporarily on hiatus after some legal inconveniences. We hunt vampires, because their fashion sense offends us. Perhaps, once the children have gone to bed, we will tell you stories. But only if you ask us very nicely.
